.Language=English,English
.PluginContents=NetBox

@contents
$# NetBox

    ~Plugin menu~@menu@
    ~Settings menu~@settingsmenu@
    ~Configuration options~@config@
    ~Session/connection~@session@
    ~Command line~@cmdline@
    ~Commands menu~@commands@
    ~File operations~@fileops@
    ~Synchronization~@sync@
    ~Queue~@queue@
    ~Editor integration~@editor@
    ~Security~@security@
    ~Protocols~@protocols@
    ~Error messages~@errors@
    ~Plugin GUIDs~@guids@
    ~Macro functions~@macro@
    ~About~@author@

@settingsmenu
$# Settings Menu

  #Interface#
     Open dialog for interface settings.

  #Confirmations#
     Open dialog for confirmation settings.

  #Panel#
     Open dialog for panel settings.

  #Transfer#
     Open dialog for transfer settings.

  #Background/Queue#
     Open dialog for background queue settings.

  #Endurance#
     Open dialog for endurance (keep-alive) settings.

  #Transfer Editor#
     Open dialog for editor integration settings.

  #Logging#
     Open dialog for logging settings.

  #Integration#
     Open dialog for external tool integration (PuTTY, Pageant, etc.).

  #About#
     Show plugin information.

@config
$# Configuration Options

  #Disks Menu#
     Add NetBox to the Disks menu (available from Alt-Shift-0).

  #Plugins Menu#
     Add main NetBox entry to the Plugins menu.

  #Plugins Menu Commands#
     Add NetBox Commands submenu to the Plugins menu.

  #Session Name in Title#
     Show session name in the plugin title.

  #Command Prefixes#
     Command line prefixes that can be used to open NetBox
     (default: netbox,ftp,scp,sftp,ftps,webdav,s3).

  #Custom Panel Mode#
     Define detailed panel mode configuration (column types, widths, etc.).

  #Auto-read directory after operation#
     Automatically refresh directory after file operations.

  #Editor download defaults#
     Configure default options for downloading files to editor.

  #Editor upload on save#
     Automatically upload file to server when saving in editor.

  #Editor multiple instances#
     Allow multiple editor instances for the same file.

  #Queue beep#
     Beep when queue operation completes or fails.

@session
$# Session/Connection Dialog

  The session dialog allows creating and managing connections to remote servers.

  #Session tabs#
     Basic session properties, environment, directories, and protocol-specific settings.

  #Session groups#
     - SSH/SCP/SFTP settings
     - FTP/FTPS settings
     - WebDAV settings
     - S3 settings
     - Connection and proxy settings
     - Authentication methods
     - Keyboard exchange (KEX) options

  #Session management#
     Create, edit, copy, rename, export, import, and delete stored sessions.

  #Quick connect#
     Use command line or shortcuts to connect quickly without storing session.

@cmdline
$# Command Line Support

  NetBox can be invoked from FAR command line using any of the configured
  command prefixes (default: netbox,ftp,scp,sftp,ftps,webdav,s3).

  Syntax:
    <prefix>:[//[user[:password]@]host[:port]/][path]

  Examples:
    netbox:example.com/public/
    sftp:user@ssh.example.com:2222/projects
    ftps:ftp.example.com
    webdav:https://webdav.example.com/dav

  Command line can also be used to execute custom commands:
    <prefix>:<command>[ parameters]

  For session names with spaces, enclose in quotes or use the full syntax.

@commands
$# Commands Menu

  Access via Plugins → NetBox Commands or Ctrl-Alt-Shift-W when
  NetBox panel is active.

  #Attributes#
     Change file attributes on remote server (permissions, timestamps).

  #Create symbolic/hard link#
     Create link on remote server.

  #Apply command#
     Execute shell command on selected files/directories on server.

  #Synchronize#
     Compare and synchronize local and remote directories.

  #Full Synchronize#
     Full directory synchronization with more options.

  #Queue#
     Open transfer queue manager.

  #Information#
     Show server protocol and capability information.

  #Show log#
     Display current session log.

  #Clear caches#
     Clear directory and session caches.

  #PuTTY/Pageant/PuTTYgen#
     Launch external PuTTY tools (if configured).

  #Edit history#
     View and edit command history.

  #Add bookmark#
     Add current directory to bookmarks.

  #Open directory#
     Navigate to a specific directory on current panel.

  #Home directory#
     Go to remote user's home directory.

  #Synchronize browsing#
     Toggle synchronized browsing mode.

  #Configure#
     Open main configuration dialog.

  #About#
     Show plugin information.

@fileops
$# File Operations

  NetBox supports standard file operations:

  #Copy/Move#
     Copy or move files between local and remote panels, or within remote panel.

  #Create directory#
     Create new remote directory.

  #Rename#
     Rename remote file or directory.

  #Delete#
     Delete remote file or directory (to recycle bin if enabled).

  #Properties#
     View and edit file properties (permissions, owner, timestamps, links).

  #Resume and overwrite#
     Handling of existing files, resume support, append mode.

  #Transfer encoding#
     Text (ASCII) vs binary transfer modes, automatic detection.

  #Filename modification#
     Case conversion, invalid character replacement.

  #Transfer queue#
     Background transfers that can be paused, resumed, reordered.

  #Keep directory up-to-date#
     Automated synchronization of directory changes.

@sync
$# Synchronization

  #Synchronize Browsing#
     When enabled, navigating in one panel automatically navigates
     the other panel to corresponding directory.

  #Manual Synchronization#
     Compare directories and transfer differences.

  #Synchronization criteria#
     - By timestamp (newer files)
     - By file size
     - Both

  #Direction#
     - Upload (local → remote)
     - Download (remote → local)
     - Both ways

  #Options#
     - Preview changes before transfer
     - Delete files not present on source
     - Exclude by file mask
     - Transfer only selected files

@queue
$# Transfer Queue

  The Background Queue allows file transfers to run in the background.

  #Queue management#
     - Add files to queue (copy, move, download, upload)
     - Pause/resume transfers
     - Reorder queued items
     - Cancel individual transfers
     - Clear completed items

  #Background operations#
     Transfers continue even when panels are closed or other
     operations are performed.

  #Queue limits#
     Configure maximum simultaneous transfers.

  #Error handling#
     Retry failed transfers, continue on error, prompt for user action.

@editor
$# Editor Integration

  NetBox can integrate with FAR editor for remote file editing:

  #Download on open#
     When opening a remote file, it is automatically downloaded to temporary location.

  #Upload on save#
     When saving a file, it is automatically uploaded back to server.

  #Editor options#
     Configure automatic transfer options, transfer mode (text/binary),
     and filename handling.

  #Multiple instances#
     Option to allow multiple editor instances for same file.

  #History#
     Track edited files for easy re-opening.

@security
$# Security Features

  #Encryption (SSH/FTPS)#
     - SSH-2 with strong ciphers (AES, ChaCha20, etc.)
     - TLS/SSL for FTP (FTPS)
     - WebDAV over HTTPS

  #Authentication#
     - Password
     - Public key (SSH)
     - Keyboard-interactive
     - GSSAPI (Kerberos)
     - Client certificates (FTPS/WebDAV)
     - S3 access keys

  # host key verification#
     SSH host key fingerprint verification protects against MITM attacks.
     Known hosts are stored and verified on connection.

  #Proxy support#
     SOCKS4, SOCKS5, HTTP, Telnet, and local proxy for firewalled environments.

  #Tunneling#
     SSH tunneling to connect through intermediate hosts.

  #Agent support#
     Pageant (PuTTY's SSH agent) for key management.

@protocols
$# Supported Protocols

  #SSH/SFTP#
     Secure Shell File Transfer Protocol (SFTP) and SCP.

  #FTP/FTPS#
     File Transfer Protocol with TLS/SSL support.

  #WebDAV#
     HTTP-based Web Distributed Authoring and Versioning.

  #S3#
     Amazon S3 and S3-compatible storage.
     Supports TLS version configuration and custom CA certificates.

  Each protocol has its own configuration options in the session dialog.

@errors
$# Error Messages

  Common error messages and their meanings:

  #Connection failed#
     Unable to establish connection. Check host, port, network, firewall.

  #Authentication failed#
     Invalid username/password, key, or authentication method.

  #Permission denied#
     Insufficient permissions for the operation on server.

  #File not found#
     Specified file or directory does not exist on server.

  #Disk full#
     Not enough space on target device.

  #Transfer error#
     File transfer failed. Check log for details.

  #Timeout#
     Operation exceeded timeout limit. Server may be slow or unavailable.

  #Protocol error#
     Server responded with unexpected data. May indicate protocol mismatch.

  #Certificate error#
     SSL/TLS certificate validation failed.

  #Lock conflict#
     File is locked by another process.

  #Quota exceeded#
     Server storage quota limit reached.

  Detailed error information is available in session log.

